{"title_page": "Andrew R. Morgan", "text_new": "{{Infobox astronaut\n| name          = Andrew R. Morgan\n| other_names   = \n| image         = Andrew R. Morgan official portrait.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| caption       = \n| type          = [[NASA]] Astronaut\n| nationality   = American \n| status        = Active\n| birth_date    = {{birth-date and age|February 5, 1976}}\n| birth_place   = [[Morgantown, West Virginia]], U.S.\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| occupation    =\n| current_occupation = \n| previous_occupation = \n| alma_mater    = [[U.S. Military Academy]]<br />[[Uniformed Services University of the Health Sciences]]\n| rank          = [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]], [[United States Army|USA]]\n| space_time    = 271d 12h 48m \n| selection     = [[NASA Astronaut Group 21|2013 NASA Group]]\n| evas          =  7<ref name=EVA>[http://www.spacefacts.de/eva/e_eva_time.htm EVA Time]</ref>\n| eva_time      =  45h48m<ref name=EVA/>\n| missions      = [[Soyuz MS-13]]/[[Soyuz MS-15]] ([[Expedition 60]]/[[Expedition 61|61]]/[[Expedition 62|62]])\n| insignia      = [[File:Soyuz-MS-13-Mission-Patch.png|50px]] [[File:ISS Expedition 60 Patch.svg|48px]] [[File:ISS Expedition 61 Patch.svg|52px]] [[File:ISS Expedition 62 Patch.png|50px]] [[File:Soyuz-MS-15-Mission-Patch.png|55px]]\n| retirement    = \n| awards        = \n}}\n\n'''Andrew Richard \"Drew\" Morgan''' (born February 5, 1976) is a [[NASA]] astronaut from the [[NASA Astronaut Group 21|class of 2013]].<ref name=\"NASA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nasa.gov/astronauts/2013astroclass.html |title=2013 Astronaut Class |author=National Aeronautics and Space Administration |author-link=National Aeronautics and Space Administration |publisher=[[NASA]] |accessdate=June 20, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130621011402/http://www.nasa.gov/astronauts/2013astroclass.html |archivedate=June 21, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nasa.gov/astronauts/biographies/andrew-r-morgan/biography|title=Andrew R. Morgan (M.D.) (Col., U.S. Army) NASA Astronaut|last=Whiting|first=Melanie|date=2016-02-21|website=NASA|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nAndrew is married to Stacey Morgan; they have four children.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nMorgan was born in [[Morgantown, West Virginia]] on 5 February 1976 to Richard and Janice Morgan. He attended [[Dover High School (Delaware)|Dover High School]] in [[Delaware]], graduating in 1994 before completing a Bachelor of Science in Environmental Engineering at the West Point [[US Military Academy]] in 1998. Morgan was then commissioned into the [[US Army]]. During his time at West Point, he was part of the West Point Parachute Team, known as the \"Black Knights\". He later attended medical school at the [[Uniformed Services University of the Health Sciences]], where he earned his [[Medical doctorate|MD]]. In 2005 he completed his residency in [[emergency medicine]] at the [[University of Washington]] in [[Tacoma, Washington]]. In 2013 he completed a fellowship in primary care [[sports medicine]] at [[Virginia Commonwealth University]].<ref>https://www.nasa.gov/astronauts/biographies/andrew-r-morgan/biography</ref>\n\n== US Army career ==\nFollowing Morgan's graduation from West Point in 1998, he commissioned into the US Army as a medical officer. He completed his medical training and then volunteered for the  [[US Army Special Operations Command]]. He was assigned as an [[physician]] at [[Fort Bragg]] and worked as a medical team member in the Special Operations Command as well as being part of the [[US Army Parachute Team]] as a physician. As part of the special operations command, he deployed to Iraq, Afghanistan, and Africa before being given a strategic special operations assignment in [[Washington, D.C.]]. He was preparing to move to an Army base in  Germany for a tour of duty before his selection by NASA in 2013.<ref>https://taskandpurpose.com/news/stacey-morgan-nasa</ref>\n\n== Astronaut career ==\nMorgan was selected by NASA in June 2013 as one of the eight members of [[NASA Astronaut Group 21]] (Nicknamed \"The Eight Balls\") and began two years of astronaut basic training, this included training in Russian language, robotics, scientific and technical fields, ISS operations, [[T-38 Talon|T-38]] flight operations, survival and spacewalk operations. Morgan, along with his seven classmates graduated from astronaut training and became eligible for future flight assignments on 7 July 2015.<ref>https://www.nasa.gov/feature/nasa-s-newest-astronauts-complete-training</ref>\n\nIn between completion of his training and assignment to his first flight, Morgan served in NASA EVA/Robotics and Crew Operations branches.\n\n=== Expedition 60/61/62 ===\nMorgan was initially assigned to fly a six-month mission to the ISS as flight engineer on [[Soyuz MS-13]] and [[Expedition 60]] and [[Expedition 61|61]]. Although, in April 2019, due to several factors including the aborted launch of [[Soyuz MS-10]] in October 2018, Morgan and fellow astronaut [[Christina Koch|Christina Koch's]] flight's were extended, Morgan's landing was moved from Soyuz MS-13 to [[Soyuz MS-15]], extending his flight to [[Expedition 62]]<ref>https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-announces-first-flight-record-setting-mission</ref>.\n\nMorgan launched into space on board Soyuz MS-13 on July 20, 2019, joining the [[ISS]] Expedition 60, 61 and 62 crew as a flight engineer, alongside Roscosmos cosmonaut [[Aleksandr Skvortsov (cosmonaut)|Aleksandr Skvortsov ]] and Italian ESA astronaut [[Luca Parmitano]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2019/07/soyuz-fg-penultimate-flight-three-iss/|title=Soyuz-FG on penultimate flight delivers three new crewmembers for ISS \u2013 NASASpaceFlight.com|last1=Gebhardt|first1=Chirs|date=July 20, 2019|work=NASASpaceflight.com}}</ref>. Just six hours later the trio rendezvoused with the ISS, joining the Expedition 60 crew alongside Russian commander [[Aleksey Ovchinin]] and American flight engineers [[Nick Hague]] and Christina Koch. \n\nIn November 2019, he cast a ballot from outer space in that year's [[Elections in Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania elections]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/science/nasa-astronaut-pennsylvania-ballot-from-space|title=NASA astronaut casts Pennsylvania absentee ballot from space|last=Casiano|first=Louis|date=November 5, 2019|publisher=Foxnews|accessdate=November 5, 2019}}</ref> Morgan conducted his first [[Extravehicular activity|spacewalk]] on August 21, 2019, together with NASA astronaut [[Nick Hague]]. In the spacewalk the astronauts installed a pressurized mating adapter on the [[Harmony (ISS module)|''Harmony'' module]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nasa.gov/image-feature/astronaut-andrew-morgan-performs-his-first-spacewalk|title=Astronaut Andrew Morgan Performs His First Spacewalk|last=Smith|first=Yvette|date=2019-08-26|website=NASA|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref> In November 2019 Morgan began the repair of the [[Alpha Magnetic Spectrometer]], together with [[European Space Agency|ESA]] astronaut [[Luca Parmitano]]. Both of them were assisted by NASA astronauts [[Christina Koch]] and [[Jessica Meir]] who operated the [[Mobile Servicing System|Canadarm2]] robotic arm from inside the Station. The spacewalks were described as the \"most challenging since [[STS-125|Hubble repairs]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.esa.int/Science_Exploration/Human_and_Robotic_Exploration/Luca_to_lead_most_challenging_spacewalks_since_Hubble_repairs|title=Luca to lead most challenging spacewalks since Hubble repairs|website=www.esa.int|language=en|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/spacestation/2019/11/15/spacewalkers-complete-first-excursion-to-repair-cosmic-particle-detector/|title=Spacewalkers Complete First Excursion to Repair Cosmic Particle Detector \u2013 Space Station|website=blogs.nasa.gov|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref> The repair was completed after four spacewalks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/spacestation/2020/01/25/astronauts-wrap-up-spacewalk-repair-job-on-cosmic-ray-detector/|title=Astronauts Wrap Up Spacewalk Repair Job on Cosmic Ray Detector \u2013 Space Station|website=blogs.nasa.gov|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n\n[[File:ISS-61 EVA-4 (g) Andrew Morgan waves among the AMS-02.jpg|thumb|right|Andrew Morgan during the repair of [[Alpha Magnetic Spectrometer|AMS]]]]\n\nOn April 9th, during the final days of Expedition 62, the crew were joined by the three crew members of [[Soyuz MS-16]], Russian cosmonauts [[Anatoli Ivanishin]] and [[Ivan Vagner]] as well as NASA astronaut [[Christopher Cassidy]]<ref>https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2020/04/soyuz-2-1a-human-launch-ms-16/</ref>. Following the arrival of Soyuz MS-16, Expedition 62 spent eight days as a six person increment, during this period, Morgan participated in a segment of [[Some Good News]], an internet show hosted by American actor [[John Krasinski]] to spread good news during the 2020 [[COVID-19]] pandemic<ref>https://www.facebook.com/watch/?v=222411762379863</ref>. On April 17th 2020, Morgan, alongside NASA astronaut [[Jessica Meir]] and Russian cosmonaut [[Oleg Skripochka]] returned to Earth aboard Soyuz MS-15, ending a 272 day spaceflight for Morgan, the fourth longest single spaceflight for an American astronaut<ref>https://blogs.nasa.gov/spacestation/2020/04/17/touchdown-expedition-62-returns-to-earth-completes-station-mission/</ref>.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nAndrew R. Morgan.jpg|Major Morgan, 2013\nISS-61 Andrew Morgan and Luca Parmitano check spacesuits and tools in the Quest airlock.jpg|Andrew Morgan and [[European Space Agency|ESA]] commander [[Luca Parmitano]] checking U.S. spacesuits and spacewalking tools\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.nasa.gov/sites/default/files/atoms/files/morgan-ar.pdf NASA Astronaut Bio]\n\n{{NASA Astronaut Group 21}}\n\n{